30|$|Before the Reform, {{controlling}} shareholders' {{stocks were}} non-tradable on stock market. As a result, <b>controlling</b> <b>shareholders</b> were {{indifferent to the}} stock price but have motivations in getting private benefits via unfair related party transactions (Meng and Zhang [2006]). After the Reform, stocks hold by <b>controlling</b> <b>shareholders</b> become tradable, which may reduce their incentives in exploiting minority shareholders via unfair related party transactions.|$|R
